export const UNITS=[{id:'u1',title:'NSPIRE Foundations',chapters:['ch1','ch2','ch3']},{id:'u2',title:'Scoring & Deficiencies',chapters:['ch4','ch5','ch6']},{id:'u3',title:'Programs, Appeals & Business',chapters:['ch7','ch8']}]
export const CHAPTERS=[
{id:'ch1',unit:'u1',number:1,title:'What Is NSPIRE?',subtitle:'The foundation — what replaced UPCS and why it matters for your business',sections:[
{heading:'The big picture',body:`NSPIRE stands for National Standards for the Physical Inspection of Real Estate. It is HUD's unified inspection standard that replaced UPCS (Uniform Physical Condition Standards) and HQS (Housing Quality Standards) — effective October 1, 2023 for Public Housing and Multifamily programs. HCV Section 8 voucher programs transitioned fully after October 2024.\n\nNSPIRE is operated by HUD's Real Estate Assessment Center (REAC), the division responsible for assessing the physical condition of HUD-assisted housing nationwide.\n\nFor your business, NSPIRE represents a significant opportunity. The entire affordable housing market had to adapt to a new scoring system almost overnight. Many property managers are still behind — and that gap is where your pre-inspection service lives.`},
{heading:'Why HUD created NSPIRE',body:`The old UPCS system was criticized for focusing on how properties looked — exterior paint, vegetation, caulking — rather than whether residents were actually safe inside. Properties could score well on paper while having dangerous electrical conditions, mold, and infestation in units.\n\nNSPIRE flips this priority. It focuses on health, safety, and functional conditions — especially inside the units where people live. A property with a beautiful exterior but dangerous wiring inside will fail under NSPIRE. That same property would have scored fine under UPCS.\n\nHUD also made NSPIRE more transparent. Every deficiency includes a "rationale" — a specific explanation of why that item is inspected and what health or safety risk it presents.`},
{heading:'NSPIRE vs. UPCS — key differences',body:`OLD UPCS → NEW NSPIRE:\n\n• Heavy weight on exterior and common areas → Units now carry 60% of the total score\n• Complex letter grades (a, b, c) for health/safety → Four clear severity levels: LT, Severe, Moderate, Low\n• Appearance-focused scoring → Health, safety, and function focused\n• Graffiti, overgrown vegetation, exterior caulking all scored → All removed — no longer cited\n• Scratched countertops and damaged trim scored → Removed entirely\n• No unit threshold rule → New: 30+ unit deduction points = automatic fail\n\nThe removal of cosmetic items is important for your clients. Many property managers still spend maintenance budget fixing things that don't affect their NSPIRE score. Part of your service is redirecting that spending toward items that actually move the needle.`},
{heading:'3 types of NSPIRE inspections',body:`1. REAC Contracted Inspection — Performed by HUD-contracted inspectors. Generates the official 0–100 score for public housing and multifamily properties. Properties receive 28 calendar days advance notice. This is the inspection your clients are preparing for.\n\n2. POA Self-Inspection (Property Owner/Agent) — Required annually for all Public Housing and Multifamily properties with HUD assistance contracts. Must cover every single unit — not just the REAC sample. A separate compliance requirement from REAC — and your walkthrough can satisfy it.\n\n3. HUD QA Inspection (NSPIRE+) — Quality assurance checks by HUD staff on top of REAC inspections, verifying inspectors are applying standards correctly.`},
{heading:'Your business opportunity in plain terms',body:`Your PCNA background is a near-perfect foundation for NSPIRE pre-inspection work. The core skill — walk a property before a formal assessment, identify what will be flagged, triage what needs fixing, manage remediation costs — is identical to what you already do. The scoring standard is different, but the workflow is the same.\n\nYour edge: most NSPIRE consultants come from the inspector side. They can identify problems but cannot manage remediation or control costs. You can do both.\n\nMarket timing is excellent. NSPIRE became fully effective in 2023–2024. A large portion of the affordable housing market is still adjusting. Property managers who passed easily under UPCS are now failing because they never addressed unit-level conditions. That gap is real, it's widespread, and it creates a steady pipeline of clients who need exactly what you offer.`}
]},
{id:'ch2',unit:'u1',number:2,title:'The 3 Inspectable Areas',subtitle:'Unit, Inside, Outside — score weights and exactly what gets examined in each',sections:[
{heading:'The three areas and their weights',body:`Every NSPIRE deficiency is scored based on WHERE it was found. The three areas carry different weights:\n\nUnit — 60% of the score\nInside — 25% of the score\nOutside — 15% of the score\n\nUnits are worth 4x what outside items are worth. A Life-Threatening deficiency in a unit deducts far more than the same deficiency found outside. This single fact shapes every prioritization decision on a pre-inspection walkthrough: unit conditions are always first priority, always the most important conversation with your client, and always where remediation money should go first.`},
{heading:'Area 1: Unit (60%)',body:`The interior of each individual apartment or dwelling unit. This is where most NSPIRE inspections are won or lost.\n\nWhat inspectors examine in units:\n• All electrical outlets — proper grounding, GFCI within 6 feet of water sources\n• All light fixtures — permanently installed fixtures must be operable\n• Visible wiring — no exposed conductors, no uncovered junction boxes\n• Plumbing — hot water at every faucet, functioning toilets, no active leaks\n• Smoke alarms — present, operable, sealed tamper-proof batteries if battery-only (Dec 2024+)\n• Carbon monoxide alarms — required in units with gas appliances or attached garages\n• Unit entry door — must close, latch, and provide security (Life-Threatening if missing)\n• Bedroom windows — egress compliance on floors 1–3\n• Kitchen appliances — all stove burners, refrigerator operational\n• Walls, ceilings, floors — mold, water damage, structural issues\n• Infestation evidence — rodent droppings, cockroach signs, bed bugs`},
{heading:'Area 2: Inside (25%)',body:`Everything inside the building that is NOT inside a unit. All common areas and building systems.\n\nWhat inspectors examine inside:\n• Hallways, stairwells, lobbies, and common rooms\n• Laundry rooms, storage areas, and trash rooms\n• Mechanical rooms, boiler rooms, and electrical rooms\n• Elevators and vertical transportation systems\n• Fire doors and common area egress paths\n• Common area lighting and electrical systems\n• Handrails in common stairways\n• Call-for-aid systems in senior or assisted living properties\n\nInside areas carry 25% weight — significant, but less than half the weight of units. When triaging a property, fix unit issues first, then address inside common areas.`},
{heading:'Area 3: Outside (15%)',body:`The building site, exterior components, and systems outside the building.\n\nWhat inspectors still examine outside:\n• Parking lots, sidewalks, and pathways — trip hazards, drainage\n• Playgrounds and outdoor amenities — safety surfacing, equipment\n• Building exterior — walls, roof edge, visible foundation condition\n• Exterior building systems — AC compressors, exterior electrical\n• Site lighting — functional exterior lights for security\n• Security and safety fencing (not decorative fencing)\n• Exterior stairs and handrails\n\nItems COMPLETELY REMOVED from NSPIRE — do not spend client money on these:\n• Graffiti (fully removed — not even cited)\n• Overgrown vegetation\n• Non-security, non-safety fence damage\n• Exterior caulking damage\n• Common area paint deterioration in post-1978 buildings\n• Scratched countertops or damaged trim`},
{heading:'Strategic punch list priority order',body:`When you build a remediation punch list for a client, use this exact priority order:\n\n1. Unit Life-Threatening items — fix immediately. 24-hour clock, heaviest deductions.\n2. Unit Severe items — second-highest score impact from the 60% weight area.\n3. Inside Life-Threatening items — elevator hazards, stairway wiring, common area dangers.\n4. Unit Moderate items — 30-day clock, but unit weight makes even moderate items count.\n5. Inside Severe and Moderate items — important but lower weight than anything in units.\n6. Outside items — lowest weight at 15%. Address last.\n\nThis framework lets you tell a client exactly where every maintenance dollar should go to maximize score improvement per dollar spent. That prioritization is a core part of what you deliver.`}
]},
{id:'ch3',unit:'u1',number:3,title:'The 4 Severity Levels',subtitle:'Life-Threatening, Severe, Moderate, Low — timeframes and what each level really means',sections:[
{heading:'The four levels and correction timeframes',body:`Every deficiency gets a severity rating. This determines how many points it deducts AND how quickly it must be fixed.\n\nLife-Threatening (LT): High risk of death or severe injury. Must be corrected within 24 hours. Clock starts when the inspector leaves — never pauses for nights, weekends, or holidays.\n\nSevere: High risk of permanent disability, serious injury, or compromised physical security. Corrected within 24 hours (some) or 30 days depending on the specific deficiency.\n\nModerate: Moderate risk of adverse medical event or worsening chronic condition. Must be corrected within 30 days.\n\nLow: Minor deficiencies with limited safety or health impact. Must be corrected within 60 days.`},
{heading:'The 24-hour clock — most critical operational fact',body:`The 24-hour correction requirement is the most operationally intense aspect of NSPIRE for property owners.\n\nKey facts:\n• Starts the moment the inspector leaves the property\n• Does NOT pause for nights, weekends, or federal holidays\n• Cited at 3:00pm Friday = deadline is 3:00pm Saturday\n• Applies to all LT deficiencies and many Severe ones\n\nIf permanent repair CANNOT be completed in 24 hours:\n1. Provide immediate temporary mitigation (block access to the hazard)\n2. Email HUD's field office with a written correction plan BEFORE the deadline\n3. Receive written HUD approval for the extended timeframe\n\nEvidence of repair must be submitted within 48 hours of the 24-hour deadline — 72 hours total.\n\nThis stress scenario is exactly what your pre-inspection service eliminates. When you find and fix LT items before the inspector, your client never faces this clock.`},
{heading:'The Health and Safety Report',body:`At the end of each inspection day, the property receives a Health and Safety Report listing every Life-Threatening and Severe deficiency found that day. This document starts the 24-hour clock.\n\nThe report is provided each day of a multi-day inspection — not just at the end. LT items found on day one of a three-day inspection start the clock that evening.\n\nThe full Inspection Report (with the complete score) includes:\n• Overall score (0–100)\n• Building and unit inspection data\n• Occupancy information\n• Deficiency summary by severity level\n• List of units sampled\n• Details on all deficiencies found\n\nAs a pre-inspection consultant, you simulate this report before the official inspection. Your punch list is the preview version — delivered weeks before REAC shows up.`},
{heading:'Special report symbols',body:`Three symbols can appear after a property's score on the official inspection report:\n\n* (asterisk): At least one smoke detector deficiency. Not scored — doesn't deduct points — but requires 24-hour correction. A score of "73*" means pass with a 73 but smoke detector issues to fix.\n\n+ (plus sign): At least one carbon monoxide alarm deficiency. Also not scored, but requires 24-hour correction. "73*+" means both smoke and CO issues.\n\n^ (caret): At least one defect not yet scored during the transition period. Still needs correction — only the scoring is delayed.\n\nKey insight: a property can pass with a decent score and still have urgent 24-hour items from these symbols. Make sure clients understand this distinction — it surprises people.`},
{heading:'Three deficiency categories',body:`Beyond severity levels, every NSPIRE deficiency belongs to one of three categories:\n\nHealth and Safety: Direct risk to resident health or life. Fire hazards, electrical dangers, infestation, mold, missing safety devices. Typically carry the highest severity ratings.\n\nFunction and Operability: The item exists but doesn't work as designed. A stove burner that won't ignite, broken window latch, non-functioning elevator, inoperable light fixture. Severity varies based on health and safety implications.\n\nCondition and Appearance: The item is deteriorated or damaged in a way that affects long-term integrity or safety. Cracked walls, water-stained ceilings, corroded plumbing, damaged flooring.\n\nEvery NSPIRE deficiency includes a rationale — a clear explanation of why that item matters. This makes appeals more structured and client conversations more grounded in specific evidence.`}
]},
{id:'ch4',unit:'u2',number:4,title:'Scoring Mechanics',subtitle:'How points deduct, the two ways to fail, and the unit threshold rule explained',sections:[
{heading:'The 0–100 scale and fail thresholds',body:`Properties inspected by REAC receive a score from 0 to 100.\n\n60 or above = Pass (corrections still required for deficiencies found)\n59 or below = Fail — required corrective action plan\n30 or below = Fail + automatic referral to HUD's Departmental Enforcement Center (DEC)\n\nTwo successive scores below 60 may result in a discretionary DEC referral.\nScore of 30 or below = mandatory automatic DEC referral.\n\nThe DEC evaluates the property — gathering input from tenants, HUD officials, and maintenance staff. DEC involvement can lead to required management changes, contract modifications, or in extreme cases, contract termination.`},
{heading:'How the Defect Impact Weight works',body:`Every deficiency has a Defect Impact Weight — the formula determining how many points it deducts. Based on two factors:\n\n1. Severity: Life-Threatening, Severe, Moderate, or Low\n2. Location: Unit, Inside, or Outside\n\nThe heaviest deduction = Life-Threatening in a unit. The smallest = Low outside.\n\nTo normalize for property size, the total deduction is divided by the number of units inspected.\n\nExample: An LT unit deficiency has a base deduction of ~60 points.\nAt a 10-unit property: 60 ÷ 10 = 6 points deducted\nAt a 100-unit property: 60 ÷ 100 = 0.6 points deducted\n\nThis is an important pitch point for smaller properties — they face disproportionate score impact from individual LT items. One bad unit at a 12-unit building can tank the score on its own.`},
{heading:'Two ways to fail — both must be understood',body:`There are two independent failure conditions. Either one alone causes a fail.\n\nFail Method 1 — Property Threshold:\nThe overall score falls below 60. Total point deductions across all three areas bring the score below the passing line. Same concept as the old UPCS system.\n\nFail Method 2 — Unit Threshold:\nEven if the overall score is 60 or above, if 30 or more points were deducted specifically from unit deficiencies, the property fails. Official score is capped at 59.\n\nThis is where many property managers get caught off guard. A property with a clean exterior and well-maintained common areas but neglected units can fail even though the overall math shows a passing score.\n\nExample: Calculated overall score = 72. But 35 points came from unit deficiencies alone. Official result = 59. FAIL.\n\nThis is one of the most important things to communicate to new clients — you can pass on everything visible from the hallway and still fail on what's inside the units.`},
{heading:'The duplicate defects rule',body:`When the same deficiency type appears multiple times in the same inspectable area, it is cited each time but scored only once per area.\n\nExample: Damaged walls found in 6 different rooms of one unit. Inspector cites all 6. Only one point deduction applied for that deficiency type in that unit.\n\nMost commonly affected deficiencies:\n• Infestation (found across multiple units)\n• Damaged walls (multiple rooms)\n• Damaged doors (multiple units)\n• Blocked egress (multiple units)\n• Sharp edges (multiple locations)\n\nThis protects larger properties from disproportionate score impacts. It also means fixing a widespread problem in all locations has the same score impact as fixing it in one location — but compliance still requires correcting all instances within the required timeframe.`},
{heading:'Inspection frequency and the business case',body:`REAC inspections are scheduled based on the most recent score. Higher scores = less frequent visits.\n\nApproximate frequency:\n• 90 or above — every 3 years\n• 60–89 (pass) — every 2–3 years\n• Below 60 (fail) — follow-up sooner\n• 30 or below — DEC involvement, potentially very frequent\n\nBusiness insight: your pre-inspection service doesn't just help a client pass one inspection. It buys them 2–3 years of stability in the longer inspection cycle.\n\nBest target clients: Properties scoring 60–70 are in the most vulnerable position — passing but barely, likely in the 2-year cycle, often with known deferred maintenance they've been avoiding. These owners are motivated, they have something to protect, and they're the easiest to convert.\n\nProperties scoring 85+ have less urgency — harder sell. Focus outreach on the vulnerable middle range.`}
]},
{id:'ch5',unit:'u2',number:5,title:'Life-Threatening Deficiencies',subtitle:'Memorize every one — these trigger the 24-hour clock and the largest point deductions',sections:[
{heading:'Why these are your top priority',body:`Life-Threatening deficiencies are the most critical items on any pre-inspection walkthrough. Finding and fixing these before the official inspector arrives is your single highest-value action.\n\nEach LT deficiency:\n• Triggers the 24-hour correction clock immediately\n• Carries the largest point deduction in the scoring formula\n• Appears in the Health and Safety Report given to the owner the same day\n• Requires documented evidence of correction submitted to HUD\n\nA single LT deficiency in a unit at a 10-unit property can deduct 6 points from the score by itself. Multiple LT items can cause a formerly passing property to fail entirely.\n\nWalk every unit with this complete list. Do not skip rooms. Do not assume anything is fine because it looked okay on a prior visit.`},
{heading:'Electrical hazards',body:`Exposed electrical conductors: Any live or uninsulated wiring accessible to residents.\n\nWhat to look for:\n• Junction boxes without cover plates — very common\n• Damaged outlets where wiring is visible inside the box\n• Wiring running along walls or ceilings outside conduit\n• Exposed wire ends in areas accessible to residents\n• Damaged electrical panels with live components accessible\n\nCritical distinction: A missing light bulb is NOT an exposed conductor. It is a lighting fixture deficiency (Moderate or Low). This is a common inspector error — if you see it on a report, it is directly appealable.\n\nLeak-Electrical (new under NSPIRE): Water currently in contact with any electrical conductor or component is its own Life-Threatening deficiency. Always check below active leaks for proximity to electrical components. Easy to miss on a walkthrough if you're not specifically looking for it.`},
{heading:'Gas, CO alarms, and smoke detectors',body:`Gas Leaks: Any detectable gas odor in a unit or common area is Life-Threatening. If you smell gas during your walkthrough: stop, evacuate, call the gas utility and fire department. Do not attempt repairs — licensed contractors and permits required.\n\nCarbon Monoxide Alarms: Required in all units with gas appliances (stoves, water heaters, furnaces) or attached garages. Missing or improperly installed = Life-Threatening. Marked as + on the report. Not scored but requires 24-hour correction.\n\nSmoke Detectors: Required in all units — typically each bedroom and hallway. Test by pressing the test button on each detector.\n\nAs of December 29, 2024: battery-only smoke detectors must have sealed, tamper-proof batteries. Standard removable batteries are now deficient if that's the sole power source.\n\nSmoke detectors: marked as * on report. Not scored but 24-hour correction required.\n\nPro tip: Carry smoke detector test spray on every walkthrough. Activates detectors without reaching each one manually — much faster on large properties.`},
{heading:'Unit entry doors and egress windows',body:`Unit Entry Door: Elevated to Life-Threatening in final NSPIRE standards. Even non-fire-labeled entry doors qualify — they provide protection from fire, smoke, and security threats.\n\nWhat makes a door deficient:\n• Door completely missing\n• Door cannot close or latch properly\n• Door frame so damaged it provides no protection\n• Locks missing or non-functional\n\nCheck every entry door: does it close? Does it latch? Does the lock work? Ten-second checks that catch LT items before the inspector.\n\nEgress Windows: Bedroom windows must allow emergency exit.\n\nNSPIRE egress rules:\n• Bedroom windows ONLY — not living rooms or other rooms\n• Only floors 1–3\n• Living room windows are NOT egress unless a fire escape is present\n• Window must fully open and meet minimum size requirements\n\nCommon egress issues:\n• Windows painted shut — very common in older buildings\n• Broken latches or sash locks\n• Windows swollen from moisture\n• Security bars without quick-release mechanism\n• AC unit blocking the opening`},
{heading:'Handrails, heat failure, and infestation',body:`Handrails — Two separate deficiencies:\n\n1. Handrail missing WHERE evidence of prior installation exists (mounting holes, paint shadow, anchor points): Life-Threatening — 24-hour correction.\n\n2. Handrail missing with NO evidence it was ever installed: Separate non-scored deficiency. No point deduction currently — but HUD is monitoring this data.\n\nWhen walking stairs: look for mounting holes in walls or posts, paint outlines where brackets once were, or anchor bolts without a rail. Document whether prior installation evidence exists — the classification and urgency are completely different.\n\nNo Heat (extreme cold): Inoperable heating during cold weather = Life-Threatening. Test actual airflow from vents — not just whether the thermostat display lights up. A thermostat that shows on but produces no heat is a failed system.\n\nInfestation: Generally Severe, but can reach Life-Threatening based on extent and resident health conditions. Document all evidence with photographs and dates: rodent droppings, cockroach feces or egg cases, bed bug staining on mattress seams.`}
]},
{id:'ch6',unit:'u2',number:6,title:'Severe & Moderate Deficiencies',subtitle:'GFCI, mold, electrical, plumbing — the most common scored findings and how to handle them',sections:[
{heading:'Most common Severe deficiencies',body:`Severe deficiencies carry heavy point deductions and require correction in 24 hours or 30 days depending on the specific item.\n\nUnprotected outlet within 6 feet of water source (~13.4 per 100 units):\nThe single most commonly found deficiency in NSPIRE. Any outlet within 6 feet of a sink, tub, shower, or other water source needs GFCI protection. Can come from: (1) a GFCI outlet at that location, (2) a GFCI breaker covering that circuit, or (3) a GFCI outlet upstream on the same circuit.\n\nCheck every kitchen outlet, every bathroom outlet, every laundry outlet. Use a plug-in outlet tester ($10–15 at any hardware store). Shows open ground, reverse wiring, or open neutral instantly.\n\nThree-prong outlet not properly wired or grounded (~3.4 per 100 units):\nAlso found with an outlet tester. "Open ground" reading = Severe, because it removes the safety ground that protects against electrical shock.`},
{heading:'Mold and infestation',body:`Mold (Severe, can escalate to LT):\nSevere in most cases due to chronic health risk — especially for residents with respiratory conditions or children. Extensive mold where vulnerable residents live can be elevated to Life-Threatening.\n\nWhere to look:\n• Bathroom caulk lines around tubs and showers — most common\n• Under bathroom vanity around drain and supply lines\n• Under kitchen sink — look for soft wood and discoloration\n• Around window frames — condensation on older single-pane windows\n• Closets on exterior-facing walls — cold surface + warm air = condensation\n• Ceiling corners where roof or plumbing leaks have occurred\n• Behind refrigerators on exterior walls\n\nFix the moisture source first. Bleach treats surface mold but doesn't fix the underlying problem — the mold returns.\n\nInfestation (Severe):\nDocument everything with photographs and dates.\n• Rodent droppings: dark pellets along baseboards, under sinks, in kitchen cabinets\n• Cockroach evidence: feces (ground black pepper), egg cases (brown oval capsules)\n• Bed bugs: rust staining on mattress seams, shed exoskeletons`},
{heading:'Plumbing and structural Severe items',body:`No Hot Water (Severe):\nRun hot water in every unit — should reach adequate temperature within a reasonable time. Common causes: broken heating element (electric), failed thermocouple (gas), sediment buildup, or simply end of equipment life.\n\nFor older properties: check water heater age. Most rated 8–12 years. A 15-year-old unit is a risk — flag for replacement even if currently working. Proactive replacement is far cheaper than an emergency after a failed inspection.\n\nActive Water Leaks and Structural Damage:\nLook for:\n• Soft or spongy floors near plumbing — press down around toilets and under sinks\n• Water-stained ceilings — brown rings or discoloration\n• Bubbling or peeling paint near pipes\n• Warped or cupped flooring near bathrooms and kitchens\n• Wet or damp odor in any room\n\nStructural Hazard (Severe to LT):\nAny condition showing signs of imminent structural failure — sagging ceilings, cracked load-bearing walls, floors with severe water damage to structural members. Escalates to LT if collapse is likely.`},
{heading:'Common Moderate deficiencies',body:`Moderate deficiencies must be corrected within 30 days. They carry meaningful point deductions — less than Severe, but combined with unit weighting, they add up.\n\nPermanently installed light fixture inoperable (~2.6 per 100 units):\nAbout the fixture itself — not a dead bulb. Replace the bulb first; if the fixture still doesn't work, it's Moderate. Check kitchen overheads, bathroom vanity fixtures, bedroom ceiling fixtures.\n\nOne stove burner not producing heat (~2.2 per 100 units):\nIf at least one other burner works = Moderate. If NO burners work, it escalates. Test every burner on every stove.\n\nWater damage and staining (Moderate if not structural):\nCeiling stains, bubbling wall paint near pipes, soft flooring without structural compromise yet. Always find and address the water source — patching stains over an active leak doesn't fool an inspector.\n\nPeeling paint in pre-1978 buildings:\nModerate under NSPIRE but also triggers lead paint regulations (24 CFR Part 35). Pre-1978 peeling paint = regulatory issue beyond the NSPIRE score. Lead-safe work practices required.`},
{heading:'Low deficiencies and items removed from scoring',body:`Common Low deficiencies (60-day fix):\n• Passage door component damaged but door functionally adequate (~8.4 per 100 units) — worn knobs, loose hinges, missing weather stripping\n• Non-security, non-egress door with damaged component (~6.2 per 100 units) — closet doors, pantry doors\n• Bathtub or shower component damaged but hygiene unaffected (~3.5 per 100 units) — cracked tile, loose caulk, minor chips\n\nCompletely removed from NSPIRE — do NOT spend client money here:\n• Graffiti (not cited at all)\n• Overgrown vegetation\n• Non-security, non-safety fence damage\n• Exterior caulking damage\n• Common area paint deterioration in post-1978 properties\n• Scratched countertops\n• Damaged trim\n\nThis list is one of the most immediately practical things to share with a new client. Many are allocating maintenance budget to items that have zero impact on their NSPIRE score. Redirecting that spend toward actual scored items demonstrates expertise before they even hire you.`}
]},
{id:'ch7',unit:'u3',number:7,title:'HCV vs. Scored Programs',subtitle:'Public housing vs. voucher programs — two different NSPIRE systems',sections:[
{heading:'Two systems under one standard',body:`Not all NSPIRE inspections produce a numerical score. The program type determines how the inspection is evaluated.\n\nPublic Housing (PHA) — 0–100 numerical score. Fail threshold below 60. Unit Threshold and DEC rules apply.\n\nMultifamily (PBRA — Project-Based Rental Assistance) — 0–100 numerical score. Same fail threshold, unit threshold, and DEC rules. Includes Section 8 Project-Based, Section 236, and other multifamily assistance programs.\n\nHousing Choice Voucher (HCV / Section 8 tenant-based) — Pass or Fail only. No numerical score. Any Life-Threatening or Severe deficiency = Fail. Landlord must correct within required timeframes or risk losing the Housing Assistance Payment (HAP) contract.\n\nProject-Based Voucher (PBV) — Same as HCV. Pass or Fail, no score.\n\nThis distinction shapes your service pitch. For scored properties you can show clients a projected score improvement. For HCV landlords the pitch is simpler: one failed inspection cycle can suspend their monthly income.`},
{heading:'What a fail means for HCV landlords',body:`For Section 8 HCV landlords, the financial stakes are immediate and direct.\n\nWhen an HCV unit fails:\n1. Landlord is notified of specific deficiencies\n2. Landlord must correct within required timeframe\n3. If corrections not made in time, HAP can be suspended\n4. Suspended HAP = landlord stops receiving the monthly Section 8 payment for that unit\n\nFor a landlord with 20 HCV units at an average of $1,500/month, a widespread inspection failure represents $30,000/month in jeopardized income.\n\nYour pitch to HCV landlords: "I help you protect your HAP income by making sure every unit passes before the inspector shows up."\n\nBest targets in this segment:\n• Landlords with 5+ HCV units — enough units that one failed cycle hurts significantly\n• Landlords who recently failed — already experiencing the pain, highly motivated\n• Newer HCV landlords — never been through an NSPIRE inspection before\n• Investors converting market-rate units to HCV — don't know what inspectors look for`},
{heading:'POA self-inspections — annual compliance requirement',body:`Property Owners and Agents for Public Housing and Multifamily properties with HUD assistance contracts are required to self-inspect ALL units at least once per year.\n\nKey facts:\n• Must cover every single unit — not just the REAC sample\n• Timing is flexible within the year\n• Can be coordinated with tenant re-examinations\n• Must be documented and records maintained\n• NSPIRE standards apply\n\nThis creates dual value for your service:\n\n1. You satisfy the annual self-inspection compliance requirement\n2. You simultaneously prepare the property for the next REAC inspection\n\nWhen pitching to multifamily owners: your walkthrough satisfies two separate requirements at once — their annual HUD compliance obligation AND their inspection readiness preparation. They were going to spend money on the self-inspection anyway. Your service makes that spend do double duty.`},
{heading:'Inspection frequency and scheduling strategy',body:`Properties receive 28 calendar days advance notice before REAC inspections.\n\nApproximate frequency by score:\n• 90 or above — every 3 years\n• 60–89 — every 2–3 years\n• Below 60 — follow-up sooner\n• 30 or below — DEC involvement, frequent inspections possible\n\nStrategic insight for your outreach:\n\nProperties that recently scored in the 60–70 range are your best prospects. They're nervous, they have something to protect, and they know their current condition is marginal.\n\nProperties scoring 85+ are in the 3-year cycle with lower urgency. Harder to convert until the next inspection approaches.\n\nProperties that just failed are also strong — they need help immediately, they've experienced the pain, and they're highly motivated to not fail again. Reach out immediately when failed inspection scores become public record.`},
{heading:'The inspection sample — why every unit matters',body:`For scored inspections, REAC does not inspect every unit. They inspect a statistical sample.\n\nHow it works:\n• Sample size is based on total units at the property\n• Units are randomly selected — the property cannot influence which ones get inspected\n• REAC uses the sample to estimate overall property condition\n\nThis works in both directions. A bad unit in the sample can sink the score. A bad unit not sampled won't affect the score — this time.\n\nYour job: bring ALL units to a condition where it doesn't matter which ones get sampled. Every unit should be able to pass an NSPIRE inspection on any given day.\n\nFor your service pitch: "The inspector's sample is random. You can't control which units get inspected. The only way to guarantee a good score is to make sure every unit is ready."\n\nThis is also why POA self-inspection matters — it forces owners to look at every unit, not just hope the worst ones aren't selected.`}
]},
{id:'ch8',unit:'u3',number:8,title:'Appeals & Building Your Business',subtitle:'The appeals process, documentation strategy, and growing from first client to recurring revenue',sections:[
{heading:'The NSPIRE appeals process',body:`The appeals process under NSPIRE is significantly more successful than under UPCS. Early data shows approximately 44% of appealed deficiencies were successfully overturned.\n\nWhat can be appealed:\n• Individual deficiency citations — challenge specific items on the report\n• Severity misclassification — argue an item was rated at the wrong severity level\n• Items repaired before the inspection with documented evidence\n• Deficiencies that don't meet the stated NSPIRE standard criteria\n\nCritical rule: Appeals do NOT pause the correction clock. The property must still fix or mitigate the deficiency within the required timeframe even while an appeal is pending. Appeals are about adjusting the score — not delaying the fix.\n\nAbout 4.8% of all NSPIRE inspections resulted in at least one successful appeal in early data. Given thousands of inspections, that represents significant score recovery across the industry.`},
{heading:'What to appeal and common wins',body:`Most commonly appealed and successfully overturned:\n\nDoor component deficiencies — inspectors sometimes cite doors that actually meet the "functional adequacy" standard. If a door opens, closes, latches, and serves its purpose, a minor component issue may not qualify. Review the exact NSPIRE criteria before accepting any door citation.\n\nOutlet grounding issues — when a GFCI breaker upstream provides protection not visible at the outlet. The plug tester may show "open ground" but if a GFCI breaker covers that circuit, the outlet is actually protected. An electrician's documentation of upstream GFCI protection can win this appeal.\n\nInfestation citations — when active pest control records exist but weren't shown during the walkthrough. A pest control contract with recent service dates and treatment logs can overturn the citation.\n\nSeverity misclassification — if an item was cited as Severe when Moderate criteria more accurately applies. Reduces the point deduction even if the deficiency itself stands.\n\nMissing light bulb cited as exposed conductor — directly appealable based on NSPIRE standard language.`},
{heading:'Documentation strategy',body:`Build documentation systems for clients before they need them — not after a bad inspection.\n\nWork orders with completion dates:\nEvery repair logged with date requested, date completed, and technician. This is the primary evidence for showing items were repaired. If a client doesn't have a work order system, help them set one up.\n\nContractor invoices and receipts:\nFor third-party repairs — electrical, pest control, plumbing. Dated invoice from a licensed contractor showing specific work performed is strong appeal evidence.\n\nTime-stamped photographs:\nSmartphone photos include GPS coordinates and timestamps in file metadata. Take "after" photos of every repair, organized by unit and date. When filing an appeal, this library is your evidence.\n\nInspection certificates:\nElevator, boiler, fire system — show systems were professionally inspected and cleared.\n\nPest control service records:\nActive contracts with service logs showing dates and treatments. Critical for infestation appeals.\n\nPro tip: Create a property documentation binder (digital or physical) for each client organized by unit number. Update after each repair. When you need to file an appeal, you pull the package in minutes instead of scrambling.`},
{heading:'Your full-service business model',body:`Five natural service phases, each generating its own revenue:\n\nPhase 1 — Pre-Inspection Walkthrough:\nWalk the property with NSPIRE checklist, simulate the score, deliver a prioritized punch list. Core service.\nPricing: $15–35 per unit, minimum $1,500–2,500\n\nPhase 2 — Remediation Management:\nCoordinate repairs from the punch list. Get multiple bids. Negotiate contractor pricing (your PCNA background).\nPricing: % of project savings or flat management fee (5–15% of project cost)\n\nPhase 3 — Pre-Inspection Re-Walk:\nReturn before the official REAC inspection to confirm all punch list items are resolved. Issue a clearance report.\nPricing: Flat fee $500–1,500 depending on property size\n\nPhase 4 — Post-Inspection Appeals:\nReview the REAC report, identify appealable items, compile documentation package, submit the appeal.\nPricing: Flat fee $1,000–2,500 per appeal package\n\nPhase 5 — Annual Retainer:\nConduct the annual POA self-inspection, quarterly walkthroughs, staff training.\nPricing: Monthly flat rate $500–3,000 depending on portfolio size`},
{heading:'Getting your first client and scaling',body:`Your first client is the most important one — it becomes the case study that opens every door after.\n\nGetting started:\n• Your contact in the business is your starting point — get a warm intro to one property with an inspection coming up in 60–90 days\n• Offer a discounted first engagement in exchange for a documented case study and testimonial\n• Do the work thoroughly. Document everything. Track before-and-after score.\n\nA case study with specific results — "identified 23 deficiencies, helped property go from a projected fail to a score of 74, saved $28K in over-priced repair estimates" — is worth more than any marketing material.\n\nWhere to find more clients:\n• Property management companies with 5+ affordable housing properties\n• State housing finance agencies often know which properties are struggling\n• HUD-approved lenders and LIHTC syndicators want assets inspection-ready before year-15 audits\n• Affordable housing attorneys and CPAs are excellent referral sources\n\nScaling: once you have 3–5 case studies, hire trained walkers to do field work while you handle client relationships and remediation strategy. Your PCNA background and cost negotiation skill are the irreplaceable pieces — those scale through your oversight, not your physical presence at every property.`}
]}]

